{
  "texts": [
    "As CompAct decompresses the gradients back to full size only for the update step, it compresses a large part of the compute graph, which in turn translates to major memory savings.",
    "Figure 2 presents an overview of our method, while For a given linear layer x i+1 = x i W i+1, we project its input x i using a random projection matrix P, and save the result z i for the backward pass.",
    "During the backward pass, we first compute the compressed gradients Ĝi and update the optimizer's parameter update function ρ t (Ĝi).",
    "For Adam, ρ t represents gradient normalization using the first and second gradient moments.",
    "Finally, we decompress the gradient back to the full parameter size Gi and perform an update step."
  ]
}